# Known divergences between pgaudit's audit stream through multigateway and
# upstream's expected output. Generated against a cluster with PR #1140
# (refresh pooled connections on ALTER DATABASE/ROLE SET) merged — the suite's
# role-level `ALTER ROLE … SET pgaudit.*` settings only reach pooled backends
# with that fix. Four divergence classes, all deterministic (the run is
# byte-stable after ResultNormalizers, which neutralize the per-backend
# STATEMENT_ID counter and psql's ON_ERROR_ROLLBACK savepoint audits):
#
# 1. No audit records for SET / RESET / SET ROLE statements (the missing
#    `MISC,SET` / `MISC,RESET` lines). multigateway owns session settings BY
#    DESIGN: a client SET is absorbed into the gateway's session-state
#    tracking and applied to backends through pg_catalog.set_config(), so the
#    backend — and therefore pgaudit — never sees the literal SET statement.
#    pgaudit audits what the backend executes; through a transaction pooler
#    that is genuinely a different statement stream.
#
# 2. No audit records for SQL-level PREPARE / EXECUTE / DEALLOCATE under their
#    upstream names. The gateway owns SQL-level prepared statements (the same
#    by-design behavior documented for pgtap's prepared-statement fixtures in
#    PR #1141); the backend sees the gateway's extended-protocol execution,
#    not the client's PREPARE text.
#
# 3. Gateway-rejected statements (CREATE/ALTER/DROP DATABASE, CREATE SERVER /
#    postgres_fdw objects): rejected by multigateway before any backend sees
#    them (Tier-2 unsafe statements), so the audit records and the follow-on
#    output for those objects don't exist; their ERROR lines appear instead.
#
# 4. PRODUCT GAP, absorbed here pending a fix (the two "Test for MISC
#    commands" sections that end in "current transaction is aborted"
#    cascades): after the suite runs `SET ROLE regress_alice` (non-superuser)
#    inside a transaction, the gateway's session-settings replay re-applies
#    the tracked superuser-only pgaudit.* GUCs under the now-active alice
#    role, failing with `permission denied to set parameter "pgaudit.log"`
#    outside psql's savepoint protocol and aborting the transaction; the
#    section's remaining statements then no-op. Upstream runs these sections
#    cleanly. Not addressed by PRs #1137-#1140 (verified empirically: the
#    hunks are identical with and without #1138). When the replay-under-
#    SET-ROLE behavior is fixed, regenerate this patch — these hunks (the
#    ones around "permission denied to set parameter") must disappear.
